## 2. Base attrs — every widget has these

All widgets inherit these from `TkinterWidgetBase` / `TkinterBase`:

```json
{
  "styling.backgroundColor": "#hexcolor",
  "styling.foregroundColor": "#hexcolor",
  "styling.hover.hoverBgEnabled": false,
  "styling.hover.hoverBg": "#hexcolor",
  "styling.borderWidth": 1,
  "styling.borderColor": "#hexcolor",
  "styling.borderRadius": 4,
  "eventHandlers": [],
  "cursor": "",
  "layout": { "layout": "absolute" }
}
```

---

## 3. cursor attr — critical rule

**ALWAYS set `"cursor": ""` (empty string) in every widget's attrs when
targeting the PySide framework.**

PyUIBuilder's PySide code generator takes the cursor string value and emits it
verbatim as `qc.Qt.{value}` — it does NOT map any cursor name to a valid
PySide6 enum. This means:

| Value in attrs | Generated (broken) code     |
|----------------|-----------------------------|
| `"pointer"`    | `qc.Qt.pointer`  → crash    |
| `"hand2"`      | `qc.Qt.hand2`    → crash    |
| `"arrow"`      | `qc.Qt.arrow`    → crash    |
| `""`           | (no cursor line generated)  |

**Rule: always use `""`. Add cursor styling in hand-written Python after export.**

To add a pointing-hand cursor in hand-written PySide6:
```python
widget.setCursor(qc.Qt.CursorShape.PointingHandCursor)
```

---

## 4. Layout types (from layouts.js)

```json
{ "layout": "absolute" }   // absolute pixel positioning (use this always for .pyui files)
{ "layout": "flex", "gap": 10, "direction": "row" }  // flex/pack layout
{ "layout": "grid" }       // grid layout
```

In the `.pyui` format, use `"absolute"` layout for predictable drag-and-drop behavior.

---

## 5. .pyui file schema

```json
{
  "framework": "PySide",
  "projectName": "string",
  "canvasData": [ /* widget tree — see §6 */ ],
  "code": ""
}
```

**`framework` values:** `"PySide"` | `"tkinter"` | `"CustomTkinter"`

---

## 6. Widget object schema

Every entry in `canvasData` or in a `children` array:

```json
{
  "id": "widgetClass_19charalphanumeric",
  "children": [],
  "parent": "parent_widget_id_or_empty_string",
  "initialData": {
    "zIndex": 0,
    "selected": false,
    "widgetName": "human readable name",
    "pos": { "x": 0.0, "y": 0.0 },
    "size": { "width": 100, "height": 40 },
    "fitContent": { "width": false, "height": false },
    "widgetContainer": "canvas",
    "parentLayout": null,
    "positionType": "absolute",
    "attrs": { /* widget-specific attrs */ },
    "draggable": true
  },
  "extraProps": {},
  "widgetClass": "button"
}
```

**`widgetContainer` rules:**
- `"canvas"` — only for `main_window` (the top-level window on the canvas)
- `"widget"` — for every other widget (children inside a window or frame)

**`parentLayout` rules:**
- `null` — only for `main_window`
- `{ "layout": "absolute" }` — for all children when parent uses absolute layout

**`positionType`** — always `"absolute"`

**Position coordinates** are in pixels, relative to the parent widget's top-left corner (0,0).

---

## 7. main_window extras

`main_window` has additional fields at the `initialData` level (NOT inside `attrs`):

```json
"initialData": {
  ...
  "draggable": true,
  "menuData": [
    {
      "name": "File",
      "items": [
        { "name": "New", "items": [] }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
```

And these extra attrs:
```json
"attrs": {
  "initialPosition.x": 0,
  "initialPosition.y": 0,
  "initialPosition.positionList": "",
  "resizable.x": true,
  "resizable.y": true,
  "maximized": false,
  "title": "Window Title",
  "menuHidden": false,
  "logo": ""
}
```

---

## 8. One main_window per canvasData — HARD RULE

`canvasData` can only contain **one `main_window`** entry. PyUIBuilder will not
load the file if there are multiple main windows. Use frames inside the single
window to represent tabs or sections.

---

## 9. Known bugs in PyUIBuilder's PySide code generator

When PyUIBuilder generates `main.py` from a `.pyui` file with `framework: "PySide"`,
the generated code contains several errors that must be fixed manually:

| Generated (wrong)                  | Correct PySide6                                    |
|------------------------------------|----------------------------------------------------|
| `qc.Qt.pointer`                    | `qc.Qt.CursorShape.PointingHandCursor`             |
| `qc.Qt.hand2`                      | `qc.Qt.CursorShape.PointingHandCursor`             |
| `qc.Qt.{any_cursor_name}`          | See §3 — best fix is to remove the setCursor line  |
| `qc.Qt.AlignCenter`                | `qc.Qt.AlignmentFlag.AlignCenter`                  |
| `qc.Qt.AlignLeft`                  | `qc.Qt.AlignmentFlag.AlignLeft`                    |
| `qc.Qt.AlignRight`                 | `qc.Qt.AlignmentFlag.AlignRight`                   |
| `qc.Qt.Horizontal`                 | `qc.Qt.Orientation.Horizontal`                     |
| `qc.Qt.Vertical`                   | `qc.Qt.Orientation.Vertical`                       |
| `frame_x = qw.QFrame(p)\n` ×2     | Remove the duplicate line (frames declared twice)  |

**Fix script for generated main.py:**
```python
import re, pathlib
p = pathlib.Path(".pyrunner/main.py")
src = p.read_text(encoding="utf-8")
# Cursor: any qc.Qt.<cursor_name> → remove the whole setCursor line
src = re.sub(r'.*\.setCursor\(qc\.Qt\.\w+\)\n', '', src)
src = src.replace("qc.Qt.AlignCenter", "qc.Qt.AlignmentFlag.AlignCenter")
src = src.replace("qc.Qt.AlignLeft", "qc.Qt.AlignmentFlag.AlignLeft")
src = src.replace("qc.Qt.AlignRight", "qc.Qt.AlignmentFlag.AlignRight")
src = src.replace("qc.Qt.Horizontal", "qc.Qt.Orientation.Horizontal")
src = src.replace("qc.Qt.Vertical", "qc.Qt.Orientation.Vertical")
# remove duplicate frame declarations
src = re.sub(r'(frame_\w+ = qw\.QFrame\([^)]+\))\n\1', r'\1', src)
p.write_text(src, encoding="utf-8")
```

